ting. Divided into analytical and pedagogical sections, the chapters present a range of possibilities for thinking about these literatures. Contributors address such genres as biography, the graphic novel, alternate history, midrash, poetry, and third-generation and hidden-child Holocaust narratives. Both canonical and contemporary authors are covered, including Michael Chabon, Nathan Englander, Anne Frank, Dara Horn, Joe Kupert, Philip Roth, and William Styron.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 4aEducation : Education. 4aHistory : Holocaust Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAarons, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAarons, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCanales, Gustavo Sánchez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemsky, Jeffrey Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlanzbaum, Hilene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodhart, Sandor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Andrew M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLassner, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevitsky, Holli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevitsky, Holli, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMazur, Zygmunt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c